Let $Z = re^{i\theta}.$  Then from $Z^2 = 32i,$ $r^2 e^{2i \theta} = 32e^{i \pi / 2},$ so $r^2 = 32,$ $r = 4 \sqrt{2}.$

Then from $Z = re^{i \theta},$ $r = 4 \sqrt{2},$ so $Z = 4 \sqrt{2} e^{i \theta}.$

Also,
\begin{align*}
(Z^2)^{1/2} &= 32i^{1/2} \\
Z^2 &= 32e^{i \pi / 4} \\
Z &= 4 e^{i \pi / 8} \\
&= 4 \left( \cos \frac{\pi}{8} + i \sin \frac{\pi}{8} \right).
\end{align*}Hence, the fifth roots of $Z$ are
\[2 \sqrt{2} \left( \cos \frac{\pi}{8} + i \sin \frac{\pi}{8} \right)^{\frac{1}{5}}.\][asy]
unitsize (0.6 cm);

int i;

pair[] A, B, C, D, E, F, O;
pair C1, C2;

C1 = intersectionpoint(arc((1,0),8*pi/48,3*pi/2,5*pi/2),arc((0,0),2,0,pi));
C2 = (-C1.x,-C1.y);

A[0] = rotate(180/8)*(1,0);
O[0] = (0,0);

draw(Circle(O[0],2),red);

label("$\theta$", C1/2, dir(180));
dot("$A$", C1, SE);
dot("$B$", C2, NW);
[/asy]

Since $\cos 2 \theta = 2 \cos^2 \theta - 1 = \frac{4}{8} - 1 = -\frac{1}{2}$ is negative, the principal fifth root is obtained by taking half the angle.

Therefore,
\begin{align*}
Z &= 2 \sqrt{2} \left( \cos \frac{\pi}{16} + i \sin \frac{\pi}{16} \right)^{\frac{1}{5}} \\
&= 2 \sqrt{2} \left( \cos \frac{\pi + 2 \pi k}{10} + i \sin \frac{\pi + 2 \pi k}{10} \right) \\
&= 2 \sqrt{2} \left( \cos \frac{\pi}{10} + i \sin \frac{\pi}{10} \right)
\end{align*}for $k = 0, 1, 2, 3, 4.$  Therefore, the fifth roots of $Z$ are
\[2 \sqrt{2} \left( \cos \frac{\pi}{10} + i \sin \frac{\pi}{10} \right), 2 \sqrt{2} \left( \cos \frac{3 \pi}{10} + i \sin \frac{3 \pi}{10} \right), 2 \sqrt{2} \left( \cos \frac{5 \pi}{10} + i \sin \frac{5 \pi}{10} \right), 2 \sqrt{2} \left( \cos \frac{7 \pi}{10} + i \sin \frac{7 \pi}{10} \right), 2 \sqrt{2} \left( \cos \frac{9 \pi}{10} + i \sin \frac{9 \pi}{10} \right).\]
